data: {"type":"response.completed","sequence_number":253,"response":{"id":"resp_04bc03112e5c87fe00692e2bfc808481959b53c24d65a46522","object":"response","created_at":1764633596,"status":"completed","background":false,"content_filters":null,"error":null,"incomplete_details":null,"instructions":"You are a helpful agent that can use MCP tools to assist users. Use the available MCP tools to answer questions and perform tasks.","max_output_tokens":null,"max_tool_calls":null,"model":"gpt-5-mini","output":[{"type":"mcp_call","id":"mcp_04bc03112e5c87fe00692e2bfcd4688195b9837b48322a56cb","status":"completed","approval_request_id":"mcpr_04bc03112e5c87fe00692e2bf958488195a9230529dc9abd07","server_label":"api-specs","name":"fetch_generic_url_content","arguments":"{\"url\":\"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/main/README.md\"}","output":"# Azure REST API Specifications\n\n## Description\n\nThis repository is the canonical source for REST API specifications for Microsoft Azure. You can learn more about it [here](https://eng.ms/docs/products/azure-developer-experience/design/api-specs-pr/api-repos).\n\n## Getting started\n\nIf you're a Microsoft employee looking for information about all of the repositories and steps for Azure SDK Libraries Releases, go to the [aka.ms/azsdk/join](https://aka.ms/azsdk/join).\n\nExternal Contributors can read [Getting Started with OpenAPI Specifications](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/blob/main/documentation/Getting%20started%20with%20OpenAPI%20specifications.md).\n\n<!-- Please check the [announcements page](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/wiki/Announcements) for any new updates since your last visit.-->\n\n### Terminology\n\n- **Offerings**, **Skus**, and **Features** - These are distinct entities represented in Eco Manager and Service Tree.  While the Offering/Sku/Feature entities and hierarchy represent the externally marketed product, **service/components** entities in service tree represent corresponding engineering entities that together power these external products.  Refer to [Product Taxonomy](https://dev.azure.com/msazure/AzureWiki/_wiki/wikis/AzureWiki.wiki/40783/Service-Tree-Product-Taxonomy) for details.\n\n- **Resource Provider** - When a service onboards new functionality onto ARM, it is required to complete [Resource Provider Registration](https://armwiki.azurewebsites.net/rp_onboarding/ResourceProviderRegistration.html).  For existing **Resource Provider to Service Mapping**, refer to [Match resource provider to service](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/azure-resource-manager/management/azure-services-resource-providers#match-resource-provider-to-service)*\n\n## Directory Structure\n\nSee [aka.ms/azsdk/spec-dirs](https://aka.ms/azsdk/spec-dirs).\n\n## Examples\n\nThese examples provide a starting point for how a library should be structured, as well as the expected options that libraries should use:\n\n* Data plane: [https://aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-dpg](https://aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-dpg)\n* Management plane (ARM): [https://aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-mpg](https://aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-mpg)\n\n## Next steps\n\nThe next step in the process after a spec is completed is to generate SDKs and API reference documentation. If you're a Microsoft employee, go to the [Azure SDK - Internal Wiki](https://aka.ms/jointhesdk) for more information.\n\nExternal Contributors can read [Getting Started with OpenAPI Specifications](https://github.com/Azure/azure-rest-api-specs/blob/main/documentation/Getting%20started%20with%20OpenAPI%20specifications.md).\n\n---\n_This project has adopted the [Microsoft Open Source Code of Conduct](https://opensource.microsoft.com/codeofconduct/). For more information see the [Code of Conduct FAQ](https://opensource.microsoft.com/codeofconduct/faq/) or contact [opencode@microsoft.com](mailto:opencode@microsoft.com) with any additional questions or comments._\n\n\n"},{"type":"reasoning","id":"rs_04bc03112e5c87fe00692e2c000e448195806d6ee5c8bcb874","summary":[]},{"type":"message","id":"msg_04bc03112e5c87fe00692e2c01006081959e58a62d3de8b73f","status":"completed","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"output_text","text":"Here’s a concise summary of the Azure REST API Specifications README:\n\n- Purpose: This repository is the canonical source for Microsoft Azure REST API specifications.\n- Audience / Getting started:\n  - Microsoft employees: follow internal guidance (aka.ms/azsdk/join) and internal Azure SDK wiki for next steps.\n  - External contributors: start with the “Getting Started with OpenAPI Specifications” guide in the repository’s documentation.\n- Key concepts: brief terminology notes (offerings/skus/features vs service/components) and Resource Provider onboarding/registration.\n- Directory structure: refers to the Azure SDK spec directory guidance (aka.ms/azsdk/spec-dirs).\n- Examples: provides starter templates/links for data-plane and management-plane TypeSpec/AutoRest configurations (aka.ms/azsdk/tspconfig-sample-dpg and ...-mpg).\n- Next steps: after authoring specs, generate SDKs and API reference docs (internal and external guidance links provided).\n- Governance: project follows Microsoft Open Source Code of Conduct (contact and FAQ links included).\n\nIf you’d like, I can expand any section, list the specific docs linked from the README, or show the exact links.","annotations":[],"logprobs":[]}]}],"parallel_tool_calls":true,"previous_response_id":"resp_04bc03112e5c87fe00692e2bf35e2c819596e52a12d0f4a139","prompt_cache_key":null,"reasoning":{"effort":"medium","summary":null},"safety_identifier":null,"service_tier":"default","store":true,"temperature":1.0,"text":{"format":{"type":"text"},"verbosity":"medium"},"tool_choice":null,"tools":[{"type":"mcp","server_description":null,"server_label":"api-specs","server_url":"https://gitmcp.io/<redacted>","require_approval":"always"}],"top_logprobs":0,"top_p":1.0,"truncation":"disabled","usage":{"input_